## Abstract (~250–300 words)

```
ABSTRACT

Machine learning models deployed in production environments are susceptible to
performance degradation over time due to shifts in the underlying data distributions,
commonly known as data drift. Traditional MLOps systems rely on human operators to
detect such drift, decide on corrective actions, and manually retrain and redeploy
models — a process that is slow, error-prone, and difficult to scale.

This project presents the design and implementation of an Autonomous Machine Learning
Lifecycle Platform — a closed-loop, self-adaptive system capable of autonomously
managing the complete lifecycle of machine learning models from deployment through
monitoring, retraining, evaluation, and promotion. The platform continuously monitors
deployed models for statistical data drift by comparing real-time inference patterns
against baseline distributions. When significant drift is detected, a Large Language
Model (LLM) analyzes the context and recommends a structured retraining strategy.

The system incorporates a comprehensive policy and guardrails layer that enforces
freeze windows, cost limits, retraining rate limits, and severity-based approval
workflows to ensure safe and governed model updates. The training pipeline features
multi-phase optimization including automated feature selection, class imbalance
handling, Bayesian hyperparameter tuning using Optuna, automated model selection
across multiple algorithms, and ensemble learning techniques.

Candidate models are evaluated against production baselines using configurable
improvement thresholds, and only models that demonstrate statistically meaningful
improvement are promoted to production. Complete model version lineage is maintained
for governance and auditability.

The platform is built using FastAPI, PostgreSQL, MinIO, Ollama (LLaMA3), and a
React-based dashboard, all orchestrated through Docker Compose. The system
demonstrates the ability to detect drift, make intelligent retraining decisions, and
safely promote superior models without human intervention, thereby reducing
operational overhead and preventing silent model degradation.
```

